[{"id":26940,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>573</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>623</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>573</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>623</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16f78586-3935-4aef-a00d-998f79577e99-image.png\" style=\"width: 446px; height: 131px;\" /></p><p>Temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>623</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p>Pressure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26929,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c797f8ec-eae4-43b0-82ef-68349e1b8526-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7981f870-5d87-416b-8e08-82492fee9ad0-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 110px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b60442e2-b922-4730-8884-ba9dfc7f3167-image.png\" style=\"width: 222px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d7bc4bee-441e-4680-9290-30fde94d0021-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 116px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd071870-f9ad-4129-8563-0fca74e8903e-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 377px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26898,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/07f946eb-519c-4318-b1aa-b19a30f4cac2-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1ff4813-cdd7-46ea-9ba3-0e68731a7054-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cbcc9e21-da21-4c87-8e39-436b6b5bd9ce-image.png\" style=\"width: 244px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2f23caa4-a342-49f2-ba6e-d5426672f2ad-image.png\" style=\"width: 255px; height: 140px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The first step involve the fridel craft alkylation reaction of benzene and cummene is formed as the product. That on oxidation with oxygen gas gives phenol and acetone.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96d8ddd6-bc18-4fad-b446-76f6fec67140-image.png\" style=\"width: 402px; height: 300px;\" /></p><p>Oxidation of phenol with strong oxidising agent will give benzoquinone(A). And bromination of phenol in non-polar medium will give ortho or para bromo&nbsp;phenol as major product.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26906,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ac36514-03a9-4575-be40-178113cd1019-image.png\" style=\"width: 105px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9814d91f-55ac-4c7d-8a30-c1aa4b67be39-image.png\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50b455d1-aeaf-4858-86fd-e0a02227442c-image.png\" style=\"width: 172px; height: 90px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1ce1beb-8de4-4442-b501-880fffc7fadd-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1d7e193e-8a4e-420e-9f34-ebb5c4115c4d-17768a9e-df81-4461-ac55-6f8b7a36b526-image.png\" style=\"width: 836px; height: 149px;\" /></p><p>In first step acid base reaction with substitution reaction will take place.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26934,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethoxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethoxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethoxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Hydroxy<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl butane"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a848042c-a68c-4e5c-9ec4-46c78ab924d9-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 419px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26826,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["160","4","88","46"],"answer":3,"solution":"Reaction A: Phenol reacts with metallic sodium to produce sodium phenoxide and hydrogen gas.<br>C₆H₅OH + Na → C₆H₅ONa + ½H₂.<br>The gas evolved is x = H₂ with molar mass 2 g/mol.<br>Reaction B: Benzoic acid reacts with sodium bicarbonate to produce sodium benzoate, water, and carbon dioxide.<br>C₆H₅COOH + NaHCO₃ → C₆H₅COONa + H₂O + CO₂.<br>The gas evolved is y = CO₂ with molar mass 44 g/mol.<br>Therefore, molar mass of x + molar mass of y = 2 + 44 = 46.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26810,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":1,"solution":"In option (A), the Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene with 1-chloropropane involves the formation of a primary carbocation, $CH_3CH_2CH_2^+$. This undergoes a 1,2-hydride shift to form a more stable secondary carbocation, $CH_3CH^+CH_3$, which then attacks the benzene ring to yield cumene. Thus, rearrangement occurs.<br><br>In option (B), the acid-catalyzed dehydration of tert-butyl alcohol proceeds via the formation of a tert-butyl carbocation, $(CH_3)_3C^+$. Since it is already a highly stable tertiary carbocation, it does not undergo any rearrangement and directly loses a proton to form 2-methylpropene.<br><br>In option (C), the isomerization of n-hexane in the presence of anhydrous $AlCl_3$ and $HCl$ proceeds via the formation of carbocations that undergo skeletal rearrangements to form more stable branched isomers like 2-methylpentane.<br><br>In option (D), the acid-catalyzed dehydration of neopentyl alcohol initially forms a primary neopentyl carbocation, $(CH_3)_3CCH_2^+$. This undergoes a 1,2-methyl shift to form a more stable tertiary carbocation, $(CH_3)_2C^+CH_2CH_3$, which then loses a proton to yield 2-methyl-2-butene. Thus, rearrangement occurs.<br><br>Therefore, the reaction in option (B) is the only one where the major product is not obtained by a rearrangement reaction.<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26877,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>PhO</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeOH</mi></math>","Benzene, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>MeO</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>PhO</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeBr</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The given methyl phenyl ether can be prepared from&nbsp;Williamson Ether Synthesis.&nbsp;Williamson Ether Synthesis usually takes place as an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> reaction of a Alkyl halide with an alkoxide ion. Aryl halides cannot be used in this reaction. The reaction is given below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cabe1b84-ce1a-42a8-8133-d132c3aebf8d.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 83px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26960,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/188122d2-c607-4732-9498-ea663e54caf6-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 173px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d2011288-83f8-4263-82fb-6f4ce058a285-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1b54412-77af-4cea-ba1b-c36d528744c1-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 111px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/14b103f3-63ad-40b3-a6b5-cfb277247928-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 129px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21d09c92-0ee3-46a4-a804-95bdb3c97d26-malakdo.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 331px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26928,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/49963bfd-4331-4a68-b53c-552781c4b4f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 159px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cdfb6695-5b7f-4a7b-b757-dd6a33c95ae8-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 156px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e9b82c2-bdee-4a7b-88d8-1fa0e256eb24-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7191b163-4fba-4e79-9605-7c046f04e218-image.png\" style=\"width: 152px; height: 150px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40007081-f087-4e74-ba8e-f53dda9bb10c-image.png\" style=\"width: 478px; height: 277px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26821,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A, C and E Only","A and D Only","C and D Only","B, D and E Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"Analyzing each reaction for alcohol production:<br>Reaction A: $CH_4 + O_2 \\xrightarrow{Mo_2O_3, \\Delta}$ produces formaldehyde, not alcohol.<br>Reaction B: $2CH_3CH_3 + 3O_2 \\xrightarrow{(CH_3COO)_2Mn, \\Delta}$ produces acetic acid, not alcohol.<br>Reaction C: $(CH_3)_3CH \\xrightarrow{KMnO_4}$ tert-butyl compound undergoes oxidation to produce tert-butyl alcohol as the primary product.<br>Reaction D: $2CH_4 + O_2 \\xrightarrow{Cu/523K/100atm}$ produces methanol (CH₃OH), a primary alcohol.<br>Reaction E: The diene compound with $KMnO_4/H^+$ produces vicinal diol, which is technically an alcohol but not a simple monoalcohol.<br>The reactions that predominantly produce alcohols as main products are C and D.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26910,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>A) Phenol reacts with chloroform in presence of aqueous sodium hydroxide to form salicylaldehyde, which is named as&nbsp;Riemer-Tiemann reaction.</p><p>B)Phenol when heated with zinc dust forms benzene.</p><p>C)Oxidation of phenol with acidified potassium dichromate gives benzoquinone.</p><p>D)&nbsp;Bromination of phenol in presence of&nbsp;a&nbsp;non-polar solvent like CS<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;gives para-bromo phenol as the major product.</p><p>(A)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0edd389-34cb-4c72-8e97-b0f37e84995f-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 106px;\" /></p><p>(B)</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8fe870d5-fe9a-4dd0-b05e-a28cb446422e-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 126px;\" /></p><p>(C)&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8479b330-1dc5-4277-8eb8-4c49564637a8-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 131px;\" /></p><p>(D)</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9fbbac5-f2b9-4ce4-a9f4-5de89edd21e4-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 141px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26954,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6f9769a2-37cc-41c7-8d61-c8187b9e52a1-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 128px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4058d472-1e25-43b7-a089-c8f4594f60de-image.png\" style=\"width: 360px; height: 144px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/451c822d-de90-463f-acfa-bae36aa9ecc2-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 138px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/846a81bc-adbf-47d8-8d33-5797f3b2eba3-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 110px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"Initial reaction is Reimer -Tiemann&nbsp;reaction, which gives salicylaldehyde. Which will undergo cross Cannizzaro reaction followed by hydrolysis.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0c4b7a8a-2956-4d5c-ade8-7426720501d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 460px; height: 183px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d953e177-6645-45f0-b5e5-a70ac9ef2c61-image.png\" style=\"width: 460px; height: 193px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a671c41e-7258-4956-a9e9-f7abee24d82c-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 150px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26999,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["2-Butanone","Ethyl chloride","Ethyl ethanoate","Diethyl ether"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cg90HL3mPvsT94ppf46L7vPOnnB0NCJM1wzyeobvsYo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":26996,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Rate of reaction will be slow due to slow cleavage of carbon-halogen bond.","Alkene will be the main product.","Simple ether will form instead of mixed ether.","Expected mixed ether will be formed."],"answer":1,"solution":"The tertiary alkyl halide undergo elimination reaction to give alkenes\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/iwwruheRKnzmYkV1Z3uJnWbqBcypfmbHiXzs8-i2fTY.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Q5keBSCu7a1m5VBDi9fIqciQhiJE5qzP2DqdYC5bkjI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26874,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Except sucrose and amylose all others, give orange red precipitate with Benedict solution.<br />Sucrose is a non-reducing disaccharide composed of glucose and fructose. It does not have a free aldehyde or ketone group and, therefore, cannot undergo oxidation and reduce the Benedict&#39;s reagent. As a result, sucrose will not produce an orange-red precipitate with the Benedict&#39;s solution.</p><p>Amylose is a polysaccharide composed of multiple glucose units linked together. While glucose, a monosaccharide, is a reducing sugar, the glycosidic bonds in amylose prevent the free aldehyde or ketone group from being available for oxidation. As a result, amylose, as a part of starch, does not give a positive Benedict&#39;s test and will not produce an orange-red precipitate.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26970,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/116e0f29-d37b-4cfa-8000-1566281bc1ca-83.jpg\" style=\"width: 376px; height: 109px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47d44c56-ba90-4c59-8b10-af58fb30197a-80.jpg\" style=\"width: 372px; height: 113px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d521e8f-1762-4e9e-90e9-3ad229bac528-81.jpg\" style=\"width: 421px; height: 112px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf31078b-79bb-4624-b9c2-2152d50c89e0-82.jpg\" style=\"width: 448px; height: 86px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266681.jpg\" style=\"width: 346px; height: 116px;\" /><br />This step involves acid-base reaction at first followed by nucleophilic addition elimination.<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266681_1.jpg\" style=\"width: 263px; height: 141px;\" /><br />This step is called bromination.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26998,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Secondary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>2","Tertiary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>2","Secondary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>1","Tertiary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>1"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>3&deg;&nbsp;alcohol reacts fastest giving white turbidity immediately on adding Lucas reagent.<br />Reaction takes place through carbocation formation involving S<sub>N</sub><sup>1</sup>&nbsp;mechanism.&nbsp;Rate of reaction in this reaction is directly proportional to the stability of the carbocation formed.<br />3&deg;&nbsp;R-OH(tertiary alcohol) forms 3&deg;&nbsp;carbocation and therefore, the&nbsp;reaction is fastest.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/389d19f9-0233-4330-a80a-0b91361c4042-image.png\" style=\"width: 648px; height: 170px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26939,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eae5773c-5626-4501-98a7-795f03c82b66-image.png\" style=\"width: 302px; height: 170px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b0d533d-935c-4ea0-ae64-ebf16bc7bd35-image.png\" style=\"width: 388px; height: 169px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c5ff326-1782-4711-89ba-5cfc4e5010c0-image.png\" style=\"width: 364px; height: 180px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/18128dff-3c01-4831-bfbc-646f5994f66c-image.png\" style=\"width: 352px; height: 162px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>It is nucleophilic substitution reaction.</p><p>Here nucleophile ethyl alcohol behaves as nucleophile and it attacks on electrophilic site to form methoxy benzene, acetaldehyde,&nbsp;hydrochloric acid ans water&nbsp;as shown below:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/03a07f2f-2e4e-4082-9d17-94c95591ae20-image.png\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 217px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26942,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2609148b-0086-4ce8-a16a-29b12b5ee41b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e531d14c-6e92-49dc-8d6b-00836c4b8d4c-image.png\" style=\"width: 224px; height: 80px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/09840c42-68af-465b-8e05-bc9063ff89e1-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9615fb4b-3ea0-46cc-9f8f-b9c40a703098-image.png\" style=\"width: 189px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15ef69b9-0f06-425f-806f-57487f22f9a9-image.png\" style=\"width: 357px; height: 288px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26817,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-I, B-III, C-II, D-IV","A-I, B-II, C-III, D-IV"],"answer":0,"solution":"Cyclohexanol is a secondary alcohol, which gives a positive Lucas test.<br><br>Cyclohexylamine is a primary aliphatic amine, which reacts with Hinsberg's reagent (benzenesulfonyl chloride) to form a product soluble in alkali.<br><br>Cyclohexanecarbaldehyde is an aliphatic aldehyde, which gives a positive Tollen's test (silver mirror test).<br><br>Phenol undergoes the phthalein dye test by reacting with phthalic anhydride in the presence of concentrated sulfuric acid to form phenolphthalein, which gives a pink colour in an alkaline medium.<br><br>Thus, the correct matching is A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II.<br><br>Answer: A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26854,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fly7AxbBzy2AEZ0J3n7WtlV7l82YO8Wcdc7SW_b1NAY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wFpDQWtox72xGFquGaWSp5XXR2MKBcsdFIJrlYlQCNI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/N74caNl8G3Ta7vmPHi90URqYjro0TyOKJnZpL_gTM0Y.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xBT8k0HthauJtCbn_hU62bu1WX8ACUn4snwN_lqQGtg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/IL9abkkdfULdNC_ndEynW_z3yEa7-4MqQKArBqJmp7M.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26937,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iii</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>iii</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"(a) Alcoholic potassium hydroxide<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>used for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>-</mo></math>elimination<br />(b) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pd</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Lindlar&#39;s catalyst<br />(c) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BHC</mi></math> (Benzene hexachloride)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>Obtained by addition reactions<br />(d) Polyacetylene<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>Electrodes in batteries","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26968,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/G3I_qztiRalrYTWYP8hWiUOgGSqh5DlgxHmOKkuWIJI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DGD1QYes-bktrIxakFtOtkvufWj5cq2Wj-zsivJb1rs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9gX327pWDs0hYu036ngj1uWeWh1AZlioCXWJohTN4aQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a_FSue41izi_p7XHEH1jbeVBaEA13vNqYZ2xe6UtRHY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"PCC oxidizes primary alcohols to aldehydes and secondary alcohols to ketones. In the above reaction, $-\\mathrm{OCOCH}_3$ group is hydrolyzed to secondary alcohol which is then oxidised (with PCC) to ketone.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66X9UgV841OAOmjVsJtRKrEunek4_hx9QfBXqxFszyk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/OOLq4pp8pW8f9gUbEIh6JzRECku20bdFQg1xT5sJQUs.rendered.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":26832,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/N1kkw6siR0z64giI2_Fo1wWM3CGidm8PUEY_rdoZqsE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7VKh7wtpF6u3coEszSvBKlWIuQYn_c4mAFs98867HEs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dzp7ghCvlohTnKXfEHh0BTZIp1WxKQahjtGGW6z0QG0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HNp6VzvbyJcAIUDhn_F8p8Iw5GB-Ae7eC_X-CK2r4hA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ZhDs7YCsOyg9GcNPqmxRjhuVD6CF8QavXrxKXNuyO8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26966,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dee591d9-8e2d-42b1-a614-375c69a69c88-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 146px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56499b6f-bd94-4d0b-95c1-87eb77e64f2c-image.png\" style=\"width: 321px; height: 104px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02a7cb5c-f060-4ae7-baa1-dabd11a0d1a2-image.png\" style=\"width: 318px; height: 138px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d6b1152-dc3c-4f80-8e92-3ea73785f867-image.png\" style=\"width: 320px; height: 138px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Cumene is an organic compound obtained by&nbsp;Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene with&nbsp;propylene. Upon oxidation of cumene (isopropylbenzene) in the presence of air, cumene hydroperoxide is obtained. Upon further treatment of cumene hydroperoxide with dilute acid, phenols are obtained</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fcf5eb83-62a7-459e-a470-19df030d523f-image.png\" style=\"width: 576px; height: 223px;\" /><br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cfa231b9-ed95-4696-81cd-54f46a97cb65-image.png\" style=\"width: 378px; height: 262px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10b2e2cd-d7e1-4988-9e43-8b4cbb654e2c-image.png\" style=\"width: 643px; height: 229px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26866,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8388e5b7-791a-44c7-ab97-505f094c2863.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 169px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b21f8243-9659-4155-b0d4-61be2eb30c05.png\" style=\"width: 377px; height: 185px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0e828a4a-3921-4e44-b03c-408539649378.png\" style=\"width: 377px; height: 188px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d667b4fb-c0a5-48b6-ac3c-5e23ddd83dd6.png\" style=\"width: 359px; height: 198px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Tertiary butyl cyclohexyl ether on treatment with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HI</mi></math> forms tertiary butyl iodide and cyclohexanol.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> mechanism is followed as the tertiary carbocation formed is stable.</p><p>The iodide nucleophile gets attached to the tertiary carbon atom to form tertiary butyl iodide and the cyclohexyl group that is connected to oxygen forms a bond with hydrogen coming from the dissociation of hydrogen iodide to form cyclohexanol.</p><p>The equation of the reaction is:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c7db7bfb-cf51-485c-aa99-f2488f441c93.png\" style=\"width: 750px; height: 343px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26993,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/her1MklRhrJ6nqwRqExSXl1zvLCmozlycURr4isp6uE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oHCSATOwJbrIODo3zseN1pSmhIln23iYcaMg15tYDig.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mtlBdTlAp8sIpYA_M0Ik7Dx9QGKk2WHF2ZRAAoP-L3k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_y62KhDqe7QKt_XFaQqKOdZ-Haxonnm9YsN0Re8oX0U.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gy9AQ2DmSVP-rXdhbGq3lqzqbcSrtnqy8rmgABI5wSI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27009,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EdMrylkCiSFZ4UllsCciLwEcfNRAWhd6cKo9_1La-gw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/UInZYvA9Feh9t3OI0vFXl9PuPMS-W1kKVgvnbqZ6EGU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/IV-_JpPMoI2irVmGsYFS4HL84pG0Wd5Mn35lydijM0o.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Fns3R42W1dh2hX9J0mbJXk50Ek1cuqzRnvZgWMb4KaU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/pKlDow2TXAkszytYdlK22bXMjCKfejCY6zeHe7SaG1Y.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_v3IRjO46RUBbWoeDRLWxRJgmLZzjnLYy1OWqBfD7XQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":27005,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["a mixture of anisole and $\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH}) \\mathrm{Br}$","a mixture of benzene and $\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OMe}) \\mathrm{Br}$","a mixture of toluene and $\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{OH}) \\mathrm{Br}$","a mixture of phenol and $\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{Me}) \\mathrm{Br}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null}]